    ^.......+....{+.......!=^^^^^   ^^^^^      ... :    
    ^^^^^^^.^^^^'^^^.^^^^^^.^           ^^^^^^^^.. ^^^^^
</pre>Hmm, normally I'd leave vaults for last, but I guess I'd better get in there before they take over the entire room.  I use Recall to swap myself with the Spirit troll on the west side of the room and set to work. 
</p>
<p>
The room turns out to be just another pillar-room-style pit room.  And I don't think I can keep ahead of these crazy breeding monsters, either. After a valiant effort, and down to 490/715hp, I Recall-swap the Spirit troll back in and write the room off as a loss. 
</p>
<p>
The rest of the level proceeds swiftly and without incident.  We'll proceed to LoM 53 next time.  Oh, might as well <a class="external" href="./www.killerbunnies.org/angband/bear/bear_3.html"><img src="./wiki/classic/img/moin-www.png" alt="[WWW]" height="11" width="11">update the dump</a> while I'm at it. 
</p>
<h4 id="head-d129ac4fafc7977a974e2e29d4ce2b3b7290e880">Part 3 of 9</h4>
<p>
<strong>LoM 53</strong> 
</p>
<p>
"You have a superb feeling about this level."  Whatever.  The level starts boring and doesn't improve much.  One of the few highlights is another disconnected pit-style room, this time the four-subroom version.  I Recall-swap in with a Mind flayer, since it looked isolated&#8212;and discover that it wasn't, as I find myself in a subroom with six Water hounds, a Water spirit and a Demonic Q.  <img src="./wiki/classic/img/alert.png" alt="/!\" height="15" width="15"> 
</p>
<p>
"Uh-oh, we better get out of here." 
</p>
<p>
No, I think we're okay; another tactical swap with that Cave ogre in the outer ring just outside this subroom should take care of us for now.  I clear out the other three subrooms fairly easily, and them come back for the Water hounds.  Unfortunately, they're pinned in their subroom behind the Demonic Q and a Yellow mushroom patch.  A carefully aimed Noxious Cloud takes care of the Mushroom patch&#8212;and the hounds, which I wasn't expecting.  Last to fall are the Demonic Q and the Vrocks it summoned before I could get to it. 
</p>
<p>
The rest of the level is as uneventful as the first part, netting two Potions of Intelligence from some Dreads and a Potion of Wisdom from some Gnouls.  I'm getting close to max on both of those, I think.  Pushing on, we proceed to: 
</p>
<p>
<strong>LoM 54</strong> 
</p>
<p>
"You have a superb feeling about this level."  I'm guessing another uninteresting level, and nothing within Sense Monster range is disabusing me of that notion. 
</p>
<p>
Hmm, there are some High elven ranger in a room north of me fighting off monsters.  I dismiss them; I want those exp for myself, after all&#8230; <img src="./wiki/classic/img/devil.png" alt=">:>" height="15" width="15">  The room turns out to be a checkerboard-style pit room with some ghosts and dragons, who drop a Potion of Intelligence and: 
</p>

    <ul>

    <li>
<p>
 Gruumsh's Bottle of Death, activates for teleport level 
</p>
</li>

    </ul>


<p>
Enh.  And the rest of the level is as "superb" as the first.  I'm about ready to give up on the level when a Blue Thunderlord gets the drop on me down a corridor and drops me to 496/715hp with a fire breath.  This, of course, cannot go unanswered&#8230; <img src="./wiki/classic/img/devil.png" alt=">:>" height="15" width="15">  I duck back into the room I'd just left, toss back one of the Potions of Healing I've been collecting, and wait for him to come around the corner and get smacked down. 
</p>
<p>
One last sweep through the rest of the level reveals another disconnected four-subroom pit in the northwest corner, this time with The Phoenix as its star occupant.  I'll Recall-swap him out to deal with later, and take on the rest of the room first.  The room is fairly easy, and nets: 
</p>

    <ul>

    <li>
<p>
 The Amulet of Nahtalach (+3), with +3 infravision, sustain INT, DEX and  CHA, resist acid and slow digestion 
</p>
</li>

    </ul>


<p>
That's not even slightly tempting; leave it.  Now, I need to get back out of here.  I could use Phase Door, but I might land in the room with The Phoenix and have it breathe on me.  Ah, there's an Angel in another nearby room that I can Recall-swap with.  Now to find a corner to ambush this bird around&#8230; 
</p>
<p>
Hmm, that fight wasn't as tough as I'd feared.  The Phoenix goes down in three turns and never hits me, though it does take me to 672/755hp from just the fire-aura backlash.  It drops nothing of interest. 
</p>
<p>
Hmm, before I leave the level, I notice that a Ghast back in the disconnected room did a hit on my CHA.  I wonder if I left any Potions of Restore Charisma lying around&#8230; <em>[scans map]</em> ah, yes, there's one nearby.  I go pick that up and then proceed to: 
</p>
<p>
<strong>LoM 55</strong> 
</p>
<p>
"Wait, lemme do it, dude:  <em>*ahem*</em> 'You have, like, a superb feeling about this level.'" 
</p>
<p>
It'd probably work better with the 'like', actually. <img src="./wiki/classic/img/tired.png" alt="|)" height="15" width="15">  Some interesting monsters in Sense Monster range, but none I'd call superb. 
</p>
<p>
Explore, explore, doot de doot&#8230; hmm, there are some Ethereal hounds to our north; looks like they're lined up in a corridor.  That's reasonably superb, in the "nasty monsters" way.  They come out behind the Vampire lord and the Undead beholder ahead of them&#8212;the latter of which summons a Demilich behind me who knocks my DEX down to 18/90.  And by the time I've punched through the Undead beholder, the Ethereal hounds are coming around the corner and are about to start piling up on me. 
</p>
<p>
The Demilich, fortunately, blinks away into the corridor by which the hounds are approaching, and with a bit of maneuvering I get a proper corner-ambush position.  Most of the hounds fall before the Demilich comes back around the corner.  I pummel it down to one star before it blinks away again, this time into the corridor behind me.  Urk, and there's a Barbazu approaching from the front, too.  I take a small tactical risk and spend a couple turns Manathrusting the Demilich down as the Barbazu gets next to me.  The Barbazu, fortunately, only takes a couple turns to take down. 
</p>
<p>
"Man, this level ls less 'superb' than we thought&#8230; I mean more <em>superb</em> superb, less 'superb' superb&#8230; I mean&#8211;" 
</p>
<p>
I know what you mean, Bjorn, and yes, the level <em>is</em> turning out to be more harrowing than I'd expected.  That Demilich dropped quite a lot of high-level Tomes; if we weren't already well-stocked on that front, this would've been a jackpot. 
</p>
<p>
The level calms down for a bit after that, netting: 
</p>

    <ul>

    <li>
<p>
 The Beaked Axe of Erevor (2d6) (+13,+11) (+2), with radius-1 light, +2  DEX and attacks, acid brand, and slay dragon and troll 
</p>
</li>

    </ul>


<p>
There also appears to be a vault in the middle of the level.  There also also appear to be a swarm of Greater wall monsters off to my west. Fortunately, they're contained in a single corridor opening into a smallish room with no other exits, so I manage to contain and eradicate them. 
</p>
<p>
"<em>*huff*</em> Dude, you never mentioned we'd be fighting the <em>walls</em> in this place&#8230;" 
</p>
<p>
And they're easier to deal with here, since the main wall type in this dungeon is mountains, which even Greater wall monsters can't pass.  I don't even want to <em>think</em> about leveled GWMs in Angband&#8230; <em>*shudder*</em> 
</p>
<p>
The rest of the level proceeds mercifully without incident, and we return to the vault, which appears to be another non-match with v_info.txt: 
<pre>............'..###############.....^^^^^^^^^^
^^^^^^^^'^^^^'^#..oZooopZ.Z.Z#^^^^.^^^^^^^^^^
.........^^^^.^#..#########.o#^^^^.^^^^^^^^^^
^^^^^^^^^^^^^.^#.#'|[/#]?.o#o#^^^^.^^^^^^^^^^
^^^^^^^^^^^^^'^#.#.#.#'#.#/#W#^^^^..^^^^^^^^^
....'.......'..#.#..#'/'#[o#Z#.q.............
^...^^^^^^^^^^^#.#.#!#'#v#[#o#^^^^^.......^^^
^.^^^^^^^^^^^^^#.#'/..#...'#o#^^^^^^^^^^^.^^^
^.^^^^^^^^^^^^^#..#########.o#^^^^^^^^^^^.^^^
^.^^^^^^^^^^^^^#............o#^^^^^^^^^^^...'
^.^^^^^^^^^^^^^###############^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
..^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^.^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^.....^^^^^^^^^^^
</pre>The '<tt>Z</tt>'s here are Plasma hounds, and the '<tt>v</tt>' is a Plasma vortex, probably the toughest monsters in the room.  And after that swarm of Greater wall monsters, they're enough to push me over the top to <em>clvl 44</em>, with skill points going 1 to Bearform-combat, 1 to Temporal and 3 to Spell-power.  Essence of Speed is up to spell effect level 52, increasing my top speed to +26.  The vault nets a suit of Black Dragon Scail Mail and: 
</p>

    <ul>

    <li>
<p>
 The Full Plate Armour of Isildur [+25] (+1), with +1 CON and resist  acid, lightning, fire, cold, confusion, sound and nexus 
</p>
</li>

    </ul>


<p>
That has potential; I'll take it back as a potential swap-in.  My pack is getting kinda full, though; I'll probably want to recall after the next level: 
</p>
<p>
<strong>LoM 56</strong> 
</p>
<p>
You know what I'm about to say about the level feeling, don't you? <img src="./wiki/classic/img/tired.png" alt="|)" height="15" width="15"> I enter at the southwest corner; off north, Sense Monsters is detecting, among other things, some Livingstones (which spooked me at first; I thought we already had a GWM infestation to deal with). 
</p>
<p>
And if I were a Mage, I would have just hit another jackpot, as a Demilich in a four-subroom pit drops three Mage Staffs (staves?), including a Mage Staff of Mana (+8,-5)(40%) and a Mage Staff of Power (+0,-6) (+8.).  Man, I've <em>got</em> to get a Sorceror this far&#8230; 
</p>
<p>
"I'm here any time you want to try, lad. <em>(zizz)</em>" 
</p>
<p>
Um, yeah, that's okay, <a class="external" href="./www.killerbunnies.org/angband/ladder/zizzo/zizzo_15.html"><img src="./wiki/classic/img/moin-www.png" alt="[WWW]" height="11" width="11">Zizzo</a>, I've already got a source for my next heart failure:  my first ever with any character Storm of Unmagic, wandering around in the room I'm about to enter..  Oh, this does not look pleasant; it breathes disenchantment, which I don't resist.  Fortunately it doesn't breathe as I approach, and it appears to be nicely amenable to good old-fashioned bear-mauling&#8230; <img src="./wiki/classic/img/devil.png" alt=">:>" height="15" width="15"> 
</p>
<p>
The rest of the level proceeds without incident.  Hmm, I just noticed that the INT bonus in bear form increased again when I gained clvl 44 (now maxed at +4, I believe), enough to push my INT above 18/200 for the first time&#8212;so my spell failure rate is now 0%. <img src="./wiki/classic/img/biggrin.png" alt=":D" height="15" width="15">  And I think I will head back up to: 
</p>
<p>
<strong>Lothlorien</strong> 
</p>
<p>
where I stow sone potential swap-ins and stuff I'm stockpiling.  Hmm, I'm up to 17 Potions of Healing; I wonder if I should start carrying those instead of !oCCW's.  A quick trip to: 
</p>
<p>
<strong>Bree</strong> 
</p>
<p>
to sell off loot, and then back to: 
</p>
<p>
<strong>Lothlorien</strong> 
</p>
<p>
to prepare to return to LoM 56. 
</p>
<h4 id="head-4fdfe15be1b50d61294e4f3c3b0bbfc19f07e247">Part 4 of 9</h4>
<p>
Having finally caught up with some of the advice in the thread, I'm going to make a detour before returning to the dungeon:  at  <a class="external" href=".www.t-o-m-e.net/forum/viewtopic.php?p=36058#36058"><img src="./wiki/classic/img/moin-www.png" alt="[WWW]" height="11" width="11">Atarlost's suggestion</a>, I'm going to return to Khazad-dum and start stocking up on Potions of Detonations. 
</p>
<p>
"Hmm, that's that town way up on top of the mountains, right?" 
</p>
<p>
Yep. 
</p>
<p>
"We're not gonna have to, like, go all the way through that Moria dungeon again to get to it, are we?" 
</p>
<p>
No, I think I've got a way to get there without messing up our recall status, <em>and</em> without having to use any Reset Recall scrolls, which means we can do it as many times as we want.  First we head cross-country to the entrance to the Moria entrance and descend to: 
</p>
<p>
<strong>MoM 30</strong> 
</p>
<p>
After picking off a few nearby monsters, we recall to: 
</p>
<p>
<strong>Wilderness</strong> 
</p>
<p>
"Uh, dude, the stairs were, like, right there; we could've just climbed out." 
</p>
<p>
But that wouldn't have reset the recall dungeon, which was the whole point. Now, when we cast Recall again, we go to: 
</p>
<p>
<strong>MoM 50</strong> 
</p>
<p>
"Whoa, that's an excellent trick.  But what about those Righteous Mountains we were in before?  Will we have to go through them the long way now?" 
</p>
<p>
We can use the same trick to reset our recall status to where it was in the Sacred Land of Mountains. 
</p>
<p>
"Devious, dude." 
</p>
<p>
As you say. <img src="./wiki/classic/img/smile4.png" alt=";)" height="15" width="15">  I probably should've powered us up into combat mode before doing this, though, as there's a pack of Cave orcs right next to me as I recall in&#8212;not to mention the Mirkwood spiders and Earth hounds I discover when I light up the room. <img src="./wiki/classic/img/attention.png" alt="<!>" height="15" width="15">  No problem, though.  After clearing those out, I cast Vision to find down stairs.  Hmm, there's a lesser vault (edfu) on the level.  Should I?  Well, there are some down stairs near it, so it's not really out of my way&#8230; 
</p>
<p>
The vault is mostly populated with Dreads, one of whom manages to knock my STR down a point&#8212;but he drops a Potion of Strength to restore it with. <img src="./wiki/classic/img/smile4.png" alt=";)" height="15" width="15">  Nothing interesting therein, except: 
</p>

    <ul>

    <li>
<p>
 The Mage Staff of Fearran (+13,+11) (+0), with +0 spell power, sustain  WIS, flight and heavy curse 
</p>
</li>

    </ul>


<p>
Ooh, <em>there's</em> a keeper. <img src="./wiki/classic/img/tired.png" alt="|)" height="15" width="15">  And I just noticed that a Metal Cap I picked up from an Uruk Shaman back on MoM 30 is actually: 
</p>

    <ul>

    <li>
<p>
 The Metal Cap of Gonnol [+9], with radius-4 light, sustain CON and CHA,  hold life and resist cold 
</p>
</li>

    </ul>


<p>
Better, but still not worth toting around.  That done, we head to the down stairs and descend to: 
</p>
<p>
<strong>Wilderness</strong> 
</p>
<p>
whence a short hop away is: 
</p>
<p>
<strong>Khazad-dum</strong> 
</p>
<p>
The Mining Supply store has 4 Potions of Detonations in stock.  Clearly this is going to take a while&#8230; <img src="./wiki/classic/img/ohwell.png" alt=":\" height="15" width="15">  A quick sweep through the other stores finds nothing of particular interest, so we return to: 
</p>
<p>
<strong>MoM 50</strong> 
</p>
<p>
whence we recall to: 
</p>
<p>
<strong>Wilderness</strong> 
</p>
<p>
and return to: 
</p>
<p>
<strong>Lothlorien</strong> 
</p>
<p>
to stow the Potions of Detonation.  Clearly this is gonna take some time and stockpiling; I'll probably dip back to Khazad-dum every so often (and I'll try to be less verbose about it&#8230;).  Anyway, we use the same trick to return to: 
</p>
<p>
<strong>LoM 56</strong> 
</p>
<p>
"Looks like any other level."  Actually, the level looks more boring than most at first, until a few things happen.  First, my first Elder vampire with this character drops: 
</p>

    <ul>

    <li>
<p>
 The Ring Mail 'Belen' (-2) [+10], with sustain STR, DEX and CHA,  immunity to acid, and resist light, shards and disenchantment 
</p>
</li>

    </ul>


<p>
Not bad.  Then, as I'm entering the next room: 
</p>
<p>
<em>It breaths nether.</em> 
</p>
<p>
and there's a bright green Z in sight.  Sense Monsters reveals, yes, an approaching pack of Nether hounds&#8212;and, off to the north a bit, a cluster of Qs, including two Demonics, three Draconics and three Rottings. O-<em>kaaaay</em>, I think I'll be avoiding that part of the dungeon for a while. 
</p>
<p>
There is, alas, no convenient corner around which to ambush the Nether hounds, since they won't come out of the room, so I have to charge them. They knock me down to 575/819hp before I manage to take care of all of them. 
</p>
<p>
"Dude, if I ever get a dog, remind me not to get one of those." 
</p>
<p>
I don't think that'll be a problem.  And speaking of non-problems, the rest of the level proceeds without incident.  Needless to say, I didn't go back and try my luck with the Qs. <img src="./wiki/classic/img/smile4.png" alt=";)" height="15" width="15">  One toy picked up on the way: 
</p>

    <ul>

    <li>
<p>
 The Morning Star of Maning (+20,-1) (+4), with +4 STR and speed, frost  and poison brand, earthquakes, and slay orc, demon, Xundead and animal 
</p>
</li>

    </ul>


<p>
which should sell for a bit.  Let's see how things go on: 
</p>
<p>
<strong>LoM 57</strong> 
</p>
<p>
"You feel strangely lucky&#8230;"  A 3x1 small level, whose primary occupants of note are a pack of e's (mostly Beholders) and a pack of Time hounds. That's over quickly, and we proceed to: 
</p>
<p>
<strong>LoM 58</strong> 
</p>
<p>
"You like the look of this place&#8230;"  Even worse; a 1x1 small level, sporting an Old sorceror and some Dreads.  I take out the Old sorceror and have just started on the Dreads when guess what sneaks up on me?  Yep, <em>clvl 45</em> and the summons to the Maeglin quest. 
</p>
<p>
"Whoa!  Where'd the giant bird rider dude come from?" 
</p>
<p>
"Brave warrior, Gondolin is being invaded, and we need your help.  Will you return with with me and aid us?" 
</p>
<p>
"Sure, no prob'.  Can I finish the level first, though?" 
</p>
<p>
"No, we must go now or it will be too late." 
</p>
<p>
"Really, it's just a little level, it won't take long&#8211;" 
</p>
<p>
It's okay, Bjorn, let's go. 
</p>
<p>
"But, like, what if there's something really cool on the level?" 
</p>
<p>
On a 1x1 level with a like-the-look-of feeling?  You're kidding, right? 
</p>
<p>
<em>(shrug)</em> "If you say so.  Let's go, then, giant bird rider dude." 
</p>
<p>
And <em>*poof*</em>, we're in: 
</p>
<p>
<strong>Gondolin</strong> 
</p>
<p>
<em>[looks around]</em> "Uh&#8230; so, like, where's the invasion, dude?" 
</p>
<p>
Oh, that's the Maeglin quest.  The entrance is over there, at the west of town. 
</p>
<p>
"Ah, so that's where the invaders will be coming in, then." 
</p>
<p>
No, the invasion doesn't start until we enter the quest. 
</p>
<p>
"&#8230;Wait a minute, dude, you mean this whole imminent invasion of Gondolin thing is just gonna sit there until we go down those stairs?" 
</p>
<p>
Right. 
</p>
<p>
<img src="./wiki/classic/img/alert.png" alt="/!\" height="15" width="15"> <img src="./wiki/classic/img/angry.png" alt="X-(" height="15" width="15"> "Then, like, <em>why</em> was it so important for us to come back here in such an all-fired hurry?" 
</p>
<p>
Because if we hadn't come back with him then, the invasion <em>would</em> have happened, and Gondolin would've been destroyed. 
</p>
<p>
"But because we <em>did</em> come, the invasion won't happen until we go fight it." 
</p>
<p>
Yep.  We can even leave Gondolin and come back to take the quest later. 
</p>
<p>
<img src="./wiki/classic/img/ohwell.png" alt=":\" height="15" width="15"> "Okay, I'm confused." 
</p>
<p>
Don't worry about it for now.  We're gonna have to power up quite a bit before we can do this quest; it's pretty tough. 
</p>
<p>
"Oh, come on, it wasn't <em>that</em> bad&#8230;" 
</p>
<p>
Excuse me?  You barely got out with your life, and you're a frickin' <em><a class="external" href="./www.killerbunnies.org/angband/ladder/lil/lil_2.html"><img src="./wiki/classic/img/moin-www.png" alt="[WWW]" height="11" width="11">Alchemist</a></em>! 
</p>
<p>
"Now, I think you're exaggerating just a bit, hon.  I only lost a thousand hit points or so; I still had more than 1500 left.  Besides, I was only level 45, and I barely had half my equipment finished.  And it <em>was</em> your first time ever doing the quest, after all." 
</p>
<p>
Yeah, first and only so far. 
</p>
<p>
"Uh, &#8216;scuse me, black-n-white lady, but, like, I don't <em>have</em> a thousand or so hit points." 
